WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:02.520
This is a LibriVox recording.

00:03.240 --> 00:06.200
All LibriVox recordings are in the public domain.

00:07.620 --> 00:14.240
For information see LibriVox.blogsum.com.

00:15.160 --> 00:19.860
Treasure Island by Robert Louis Stevenson Part 4

00:19.860 --> 00:23.900
Chapter 16 The Stockade

00:25.820 --> 00:29.020
The narrative is continued by the Doctor.

00:30.320 --> 00:32.040
How the ship was abandoned.

00:35.520 --> 00:37.540
It was about half past one,

00:38.260 --> 00:40.380
three bells in the sea phrase,

00:41.200 --> 00:43.920
that the two boats went ashore from the Hispaniola.

00:44.900 --> 00:48.700
The captain, the squire, and I were taking matters over in the cabin.

00:49.300 --> 00:50.720
Had there been a breath of wind,

00:50.720 --> 00:55.120
we should have fallen on the six mutineers who were left aboard with us.

00:55.380 --> 00:57.600
Slipped our cable and away to sea.

00:58.740 --> 00:59.880
But the wind was wanting,

01:00.840 --> 01:02.660
and to complete our helplessness,

01:03.180 --> 01:06.860
down came Hunter with the news that Jim Hawkins had slipped into a boat

01:06.860 --> 01:09.040
and was gone ashore with the rest.

01:10.820 --> 01:13.560
It never occurred to us to doubt Jim Hawkins,

01:13.660 --> 01:15.520
but we were alarmed for his safety.

01:16.340 --> 01:18.100
With the men and the temper they were in,

01:18.100 --> 01:22.040
it seemed an even chance if we should see the lad again.

01:22.580 --> 01:23.620
We ran on deck.

01:25.240 --> 01:27.340
The pitch was bubbling in the seams.

01:28.380 --> 01:31.240
The nasty stench of the place turned me sick.

01:32.060 --> 01:35.180
If ever a man smelt fever and dysentery,

01:35.640 --> 01:37.900
it was in that abominable anchorage.

01:38.720 --> 01:42.840
The six scoundrels were sitting grumbling under a sail in the forecastle.

01:42.840 --> 01:45.780
A shore we could see the gigs made fast,

01:46.260 --> 01:47.900
and a man sitting in each,

01:48.540 --> 01:50.500
hard by where the river runs in.

01:51.240 --> 01:52.900
One of them was whistling,

01:53.300 --> 01:54.260
Lily Bolero.

01:57.780 --> 01:58.940
Waiting was a strain,

01:59.580 --> 02:02.080
and it was decided that Hunter and I should go ashore

02:02.480 --> 02:04.920
with the jolly boat in quest of information.

02:06.560 --> 02:08.340
The gigs had leaned to their right,

02:08.560 --> 02:10.520
but Hunter and I pulled straight in,

02:10.520 --> 02:13.200
in the direction of the stockade upon the chart.

02:14.140 --> 02:16.060
The two who were left guarding their boats

02:16.060 --> 02:18.680
seemed in a bustle at our appearance.

02:20.180 --> 02:22.720
Lily Bolero stopped off,

02:22.840 --> 02:25.840
and I could see the pair discussing what they ought to do.

02:27.460 --> 02:29.020
Had they gone and told Silver,

02:29.280 --> 02:30.680
all might have turned out differently.

02:31.240 --> 02:33.400
But they had their orders, I suppose,

02:33.420 --> 02:35.600
and decided to sit quietly where they were

02:35.600 --> 02:37.740
and hark back again to Lily Bolero.

02:40.560 --> 02:43.140
There was a slight bend in the coast,

02:43.220 --> 02:45.820
and I steered so as to put it between us.

02:46.640 --> 02:47.800
Even before we landed,

02:47.860 --> 02:49.520
we had thus lost sight of the gigs.

02:50.740 --> 02:53.240
I jumped out and came as near running as I durst,

02:53.280 --> 02:56.560
with a big silk handkerchief under my hat for coolness sake,

02:56.920 --> 02:59.580
and abrasive pistols ready primed for safety.

03:01.320 --> 03:04.700
I had not gone a hundred yards when I reached the stockade.

03:07.140 --> 03:08.840
This was how it was.

03:09.340 --> 03:13.080
A spring of clear water rose almost at the top of a knoll.

03:13.740 --> 03:16.320
Well, on the knoll, and enclosing the spring,

03:16.380 --> 03:18.320
they had clapped a stout log-house

03:18.320 --> 03:21.280
fit to hold two score of people in a pinch

03:21.280 --> 03:23.680
and loop-hold for musketry on either side.

03:24.640 --> 03:27.460
All around this they had cleared a wide space,

03:28.020 --> 03:31.720
and then the thing was completed by a paling six feet high,

03:32.060 --> 03:33.120
without door or opening,

03:33.120 --> 03:35.880
too strong to pull down without time and labour,

03:36.580 --> 03:38.980
and too open to shelter the besiegers.

03:42.520 --> 03:46.240
The people in the log-house had them in every way.

03:47.040 --> 03:50.780
They stood quiet in shelter and shot the others like partridges.

03:52.700 --> 03:55.000
All they wanted was a good watch and food.

03:56.420 --> 03:58.020
For short of a complete surprise,

03:58.100 --> 03:59.940
they might have held the place against a regiment.

04:01.800 --> 04:04.380
What particularly took my fancy was the spring,

04:05.240 --> 04:06.960
for though we had a good enough place of it

04:06.960 --> 04:08.580
in the cabin of the Hispaniola,

04:08.820 --> 04:10.520
with plenty of arms and ammunition,

04:11.240 --> 04:13.740
and things to eat, and excellent wines,

04:14.340 --> 04:15.900
there had been one thing overlooked.

04:16.600 --> 04:17.700
We had no water.

04:19.920 --> 04:23.360
I was thinking this over when there came ringing over the island,

04:23.800 --> 04:25.840
the cry of a man at the point of death.

04:27.260 --> 04:29.340
I was not new to violent death.

04:30.140 --> 04:32.540
I have served His Royal Highness the Duke of Cumberland

04:32.540 --> 04:35.040
and got a wound myself at Fontenroy.

04:36.520 --> 04:39.300
But I know my pulse went dot and carry one.

04:41.260 --> 04:43.420
Jim Hawkins is gone, was my first thought.

04:45.540 --> 04:47.480
It is something to have been an old soldier,

04:47.660 --> 04:49.440
but more still to have been a doctor.

04:50.300 --> 04:52.640
There is no time to dilly-dally in our work,

04:52.640 --> 04:55.100
and so now I made up my mind instantly,

04:55.860 --> 04:58.000
and with no time lost returned to shore

04:58.000 --> 05:00.080
and jumped on board the jolly boat.

05:02.620 --> 05:04.980
By good fortune Hunter pulled a good oar.

05:05.400 --> 05:08.380
We made the water fly and the boat was soon alongside,

05:09.080 --> 05:10.880
and I aboard the schooner.

05:13.560 --> 05:15.920
I found them all shaken as was natural.

05:16.620 --> 05:19.220
The squire was sitting down as white as a sheet,

05:19.220 --> 05:22.780
thinking of the harm he had led us to, the good soul.

05:23.840 --> 05:26.560
And one of the six forecastle hands was a little better.

05:31.140 --> 05:33.780
There's a man, says Captain Smollett,

05:34.080 --> 05:36.280
nodding towards him, new to his work.

05:37.020 --> 05:40.380
He came nigh-hand, fainting doctor, when he heard the cry.

05:41.060 --> 05:43.760
Another touch of the rudder and that man would join us.

05:45.140 --> 05:47.020
I told my plan to the captain,

05:47.020 --> 05:49.420
and between us we settled on the details

05:49.420 --> 05:50.380
of its accomplishment.

05:51.560 --> 05:54.200
We put old Redruth in the gallery

05:54.200 --> 05:55.980
between the cabin and the forecastle

05:55.980 --> 05:57.780
with three or four loaded muskets

05:57.780 --> 05:59.300
and a mattress for protection.

06:00.560 --> 06:02.900
Hunter brought the boat round under the stern port,

06:03.480 --> 06:05.460
and Joyce and I set to work loading her

06:05.460 --> 06:08.580
with powder tins, muskets, bags of biscuits,

06:08.980 --> 06:11.580
kegs of pork, a cask of cognac,

06:12.200 --> 06:14.340
and my invaluable medicine chest.

06:15.440 --> 06:18.860
In the meantime, the squire and the captain stayed on deck,

06:19.440 --> 06:21.440
and the latter hailed the coxswain,

06:22.320 --> 06:23.860
who was the principal man aboard.

06:25.120 --> 06:26.520
Mr. Hands, he said,

06:28.460 --> 06:31.200
here are two of us with a brace of pistols each.

06:31.580 --> 06:34.740
If any one of you six make a signal of any description,

06:34.800 --> 06:35.900
that man's dead.

06:37.540 --> 06:39.140
They were a good deal taken aback,

06:39.140 --> 06:40.700
and after a little consultation,

06:40.860 --> 06:43.300
one and all tumbled down the four companion,

06:43.300 --> 06:45.420
thinking no doubt to take us on the rear.

06:46.240 --> 06:47.660
But when they saw Redruth

06:47.660 --> 06:50.620
waiting for them in the sparred galley,

06:51.160 --> 06:52.880
they went about ship at once,

06:53.380 --> 06:55.000
and head popped out again on deck.

06:56.120 --> 06:58.140
Down, dog, cries the captain,

06:59.180 --> 07:00.920
and the head popped back again,

07:00.920 --> 07:02.500
and we heard no more

07:02.500 --> 07:05.300
for the time of these six very faint-hearted seamen.

07:09.000 --> 07:12.080
By this time, tumbling things in as they came,

07:12.800 --> 07:16.080
we had the jolly boat loaded as much as we dared.

07:17.020 --> 07:20.680
Joyce and I got out through the stern port,

07:21.880 --> 07:25.480
and we made for shore again as fast as oars could take us.

07:27.420 --> 07:30.720
This second trip fairly aroused the watchers along shore.

07:32.280 --> 07:34.060
Lily Bolero was dropped again,

07:34.360 --> 07:37.140
and just before we lost sight of them behind the little point,

07:37.440 --> 07:39.680
one of them whipped ashore and disappeared.

07:42.640 --> 07:45.940
I had half a mind to change my plan and destroy their boats,

07:46.180 --> 07:49.940
but I feared that Silver and the others might be close at hand,

07:50.440 --> 07:53.640
and all might very well be lost by trying for too much.

07:55.720 --> 07:58.720
We had soon touched land in the same place as before,

07:59.640 --> 08:01.580
and set to provision the blockhouse.

08:03.320 --> 08:04.900
All three made the first journey,

08:05.140 --> 08:08.780
heavily laden, and tossed our stores over the palisade.

08:09.960 --> 08:12.260
Then, leaving Joyce to guard them,

08:12.600 --> 08:14.980
one man to be sure, but with half a dozen muskets,

08:17.000 --> 08:20.620
Hunter and I returned to the jolly boat and loaded ourselves once more.

08:21.420 --> 08:23.820
So we proceeded, without pausing to take breath,

08:24.140 --> 08:25.960
till the whole cargo was bestowed,

08:26.240 --> 08:29.420
and the two servants took up their position in the blockhouse,

08:29.440 --> 08:33.040
and I, with all my power, sculled back to the Hispinola.

08:36.160 --> 08:38.580
That we should have risked a second boatload

08:38.580 --> 08:40.800
seems more daring than it really was.

08:41.580 --> 08:43.400
They had the advantage of numbers, of course,

08:43.400 --> 08:45.100
but we had the advantage of arms.

08:46.300 --> 08:48.320
Not one of the men ashore had a musket,

08:48.840 --> 08:52.060
and before they could get within range for pistol shooting,

08:52.720 --> 08:56.140
we flattered ourselves we should be able to give a good account,

08:57.220 --> 08:58.600
of a half a dozen at least.

09:00.500 --> 09:03.020
The squire was waiting for me at the square,

09:03.020 --> 09:06.000
and in the stern window all his faintness gone from him.

09:06.660 --> 09:08.580
He caught the painter and made it fast,

09:08.660 --> 09:11.960
and we fell to loading the boat for our very lives.

09:13.280 --> 09:15.940
Pork, powder and biscuit was the cargo,

09:16.360 --> 09:19.780
with only a musket and a cutlass apiece for the squire and me,

09:20.560 --> 09:22.040
and Redruth and the captain.

09:23.180 --> 09:25.520
The rest of the arms and powder we dropped overboard

09:25.520 --> 09:27.580
in two fathoms and a half of water,

09:28.040 --> 09:31.740
so that we could see the bright steel shining far below us in the sun

09:31.740 --> 09:33.500
on the clean sandy bottom.

09:35.280 --> 09:37.460
By this time the tide was beginning to ebb,

09:37.580 --> 09:39.780
and the ship was swinging round to her anchor.

09:40.900 --> 09:42.740
Voices were heard faintly hollowing

09:43.740 --> 09:45.960
in the direction of the two gigs,

09:46.920 --> 09:49.240
and though this reassured us for Joyce and Hunter,

09:50.700 --> 09:52.140
who were well to the eastward,

09:52.460 --> 09:54.280
it warned our party to be off.

09:56.760 --> 09:59.380
Redruth retreated from his place in the gallery,

10:00.400 --> 10:01.940
and dropped into the boat,

10:02.640 --> 10:04.560
which we then brought round to the ship's counter

10:04.560 --> 10:06.560
to be handier for Captain Smollett.

10:07.760 --> 10:09.860
Now, men, said he, do you hear me?

10:10.520 --> 10:12.860
There was no answer from the forecastle.

10:14.600 --> 10:16.320
It's to you, Abraham Gray.

10:16.580 --> 10:17.960
It's to you I am speaking.

10:20.200 --> 10:21.340
Still no reply.

10:22.660 --> 10:25.460
Gray, resumed Mr. Smollett a little louder,

10:25.960 --> 10:27.300
I'm leaving this ship,

10:27.300 --> 10:30.000
and I order you to follow your captain.

10:31.220 --> 10:32.960
I know you are a good man at bottom,

10:33.320 --> 10:37.000
and I dare say not one of the lot of you is as bad as he makes out.

10:38.060 --> 10:40.000
I have my watch here in my hand.

10:41.160 --> 10:43.580
I give you thirty seconds to join me in.

10:45.000 --> 10:46.080
There was a pause.

10:47.100 --> 10:49.420
Come, my fine fellow, continued the captain.

10:50.020 --> 10:51.800
Don't have so long in stays.

10:51.900 --> 10:55.260
I'm risking my life in the lives of these good gentlemen every second.

10:55.960 --> 10:57.340
There was a sudden scuffle,

10:58.200 --> 10:59.160
a sound of blows,

10:59.260 --> 11:02.620
and out burst Abraham Gray with a knife cut on the side of his cheek,

11:03.160 --> 11:05.620
and came running to the captain like a dog to the whistle.

11:06.760 --> 11:09.460
I'm with you, sir, said he,

11:09.920 --> 11:13.400
and the next moment he and the captain had dropped a board of us,

11:13.520 --> 11:15.160
and we shoved off and given way.

11:16.380 --> 11:18.380
We were clear out of the ship,

11:18.440 --> 11:21.440
but not yet ashore in our stockade.

11:22.400 --> 11:23.700
End of chapter sixteen.

